    |   |statusbar.py -- powermenu.py -- 
    |   |clock.py -- programs.py -- files.py -- 
    |   |settings.py -- tools.py -- terminal.py
    |-- core/
        |-- auth.py -- system.py -- 
        |clock_settings.py -- editor.py -- 
        |oled_monitor.py -- oled_power.py -- 
        |programs.json
    clock/
    |-- main.py -- settings.json -- modules/
        |-- dht_reader.py
---
## Version History
### Stage 0 -- Physical Build
Getting the Waveshare 3.5" display working on 
Raspberry Pi OS Lite without a desktop 
environment. Problems solved: - X server could 
not find the display -> fixed via xorg.conf 
with fbdev driver - Console displayed on HDMI 
instead of LCD -> fixed via con2fbmap 1 1 in 
rc.local - Correct resolution 480x320 and color 
depth configuration - Screen rotation and SPI 
speed limits - Font sizing for btop on small 
screen - Mouse scroll wheel rotary encoder 
pinout (A/B/COM) for microcontroller 
integration Result: display works as /dev/fb1, 
X server starts on it via fbdev ---
### beta 1.1 -- OLED Clock
Standalone script for SSD1309 OLED display 
running as a system service. What was done: - 
Time display in large font - Date below time - 
CPU temperature via vcgencmd - DHT11 readings 
(temperature and humidity) - 3.3V voltage 
display - Error status with blinking if sensor 
unavailable - Systemd service (clock.service) - 
Settings in /home/who/clock/settings.json 
Problems solved: - DHT11 unstable readings -> 
fixed via retry logic - OLED occasional freeze 
-> fixed via reinitialization on error ---
### beta 1.2 -- Basic GUI System
First pygame GUI launch on the LCD display. 
What was done: - Boot animation (boot.py) - 
Login screen with password - Basic main menu - 
Basic file manager (list view) - Settings 
placeholder - Terminal via chvt (switch to 
tty2) - X server on /dev/fb1 via fbdev - 
Autostart via ~/.bash_profile -> startx 
Problems solved: - X server would not start -> 
fixed via xorg.conf with fbdev - chvt terminal 
would not return to GUI -> fixed via chvt 7 - 
pygame could not find display -> fixed via 
DISPLAY=:0 environment variable Not finished: - 
No proper terminal - No clock sync with GUI - 
No status bar ---
### beta 1.3 -- UI Redesign
Full UI redesign with statusbar, powermenu, and 
improved modules. What was done: - Full menu 
redesign -- 8 tiles 4x2 grid
  (TERMINAL, FILES, CLOCK, SETTINGS, NETWORK, 
  SYSTEM, EDITOR, PROGRAMS)
- Status bar at top: - OLED, DHT, WiFi, 
  Bluetooth icons with blink on error - Battery 
  indicator on the right - Power button
- Power menu (popup): - Shutdown, Reboot, Sleep 
  - Logout (return to login) - Exit to terminal
- OLED settings (clock.py): - Left half -- live 
  preview simulation - Right half -- toggle 
  settings - Instant sync via 
  /home/who/clock/settings.json
- Programs module (skull icon): - Add .py/.sh 
  scripts via file picker - Run via 
  python3/bash - List stored in programs.json
- File manager: - Tree view (folders/files) - 
  Icons by file type - Popup menu 
  (open/copy/paste/rename/delete)
- System settings: - Tabs: System, WiFi, 
  Bluetooth, Display, About - WiFi scan and 
  connect - Screen brightness
- Git repository set up (Who762/whoOS) Terminal 
problem (unresolved in 1.3): - SDL captures 
/dev/input/event0 directly via evdev - Keyboard 
does not work in xterm/lxterminal on top of 
pygame - Attempts: xdotool focus, xinput float, 
pygame.display.quit() -- none worked - 
Attempts: SDL_INPUT_LINUX_EVDEV=0, 
SDL_INPUT_LINUX_KBD=0 -- none worked - 
Attempts: xinput float 7, xdotool windowfocus 
-- none worked - Root cause: no window manager 
-> windows do not receive keyboard focus - 
Solution found: openbox as WM -> lxterminal 
gets focus correctly ---
### beta 1.4 -- Feature Expansion (current)
Terminal: - openbox as window manager for 
correct keyboard focus - xterm instead of 
lxterminal (no menu bar strips) - Escape key 
closes terminal and returns to whoOS - Return 
to whoOS without re-login (bypass via 
/tmp/whoos_nologin flag) - Green prompt, white 
input text - xinitrc loop handles: terminal, 
editor, lxqt flags File Manager: - Colored 
icons by file type (py/sh/txt/json/md/log/img) 
- Folder arrows (triangle) - Action menu via 
ENTER (files) and TAB (folders) - Open as... 
(nano, python3, less, hexdump) - Copy / cut / 
paste - Create file (N key) and folder (D key) 
with name input - Delete folders recursively - 
File size display Settings: - WiFi: scan 
networks, connect with password, forget network 
- Bluetooth: status, scan, connect via 
bluetoothctl - System info: CPU temp, RAM 
usage, uptime, kernel version, throttle status 
- Storage: visual bar chart by partition with 
category breakdown - About: full device specs - 
Sound: placeholder Power Menu: - Exit to LXQt 
(startlxqt) - Exit to terminal (xterm via 
openbox) - LXQt installed with basic app set 
(Thonny, LibreOffice, PCManFM-Qt) Tools -- 
Flipper Zero style: - Sub-GHz (CC1101, 300-928 
MHz) with antenna animation - 2.4 GHz 
(NRF24L01) with WiFi wave animation - NFC/RFID 
(RC522) with card scan animation - USB Script 
(HID payload) with data transfer animation - 
Tiny Gadgets (remotes, gates, IR) with signal 
animation - GPIO Monitor with bar chart 
animation - Net Scanner with pulse animation - 
System Monitor with bar animation - Left panel 
list + right panel animation + install hints 
Programs: - Animated skull in header (jaw opens 
and closes) - Add/remove/run .py and .sh 
scripts Status Bar: - Proper Bluetooth icon 
(classic B shape) - OLED blinks red if not 
detected - DHT blinks red if not detected - 
Gray if disabled in settings - Battery with 
exclamation mark on low charge OLED: - Physical 
on/off via I2C command (0xAF / 0xAE) - 
Connection monitoring every 5 seconds in 
background thread - Preview occupies left third 
of screen HDMI: - Auto-switch to HDMI when 
connected - Auto resolution detection via 
tvservice - Falls back to LCD 480x320 if no 
HDMI LXQt: - Installed with optimized config 
for 480x320 - Ctrl+Alt+F1 or Super+Q returns to 
whoOS - Basic apps: Thonny, LibreOffice 
Writer/Calc, PCManFM-Qt, lxterminal ---
## Known Bugs
- Bluetooth does not show nearby devices (needs 
rfkill unblock bluetooth) - File rename not 
implemented yet (planned for beta 1.4.1) - LXQt 
keyboard-only navigation limited - Undervoltage 
warnings -- use 5V 2.5A power supply minimum 
---
## Useful Commands
    # Start whoOS
    cd /home/who && startx
    # Restart clock service
    sudo systemctl restart clock.service
    # Check clock service status
    sudo systemctl status clock.service
    # Enable Bluetooth
    sudo systemctl enable bluetooth sudo 
    systemctl start bluetooth sudo rfkill 
    unblock bluetooth
    # Run manually without autostart
    cd /home/who/whoOS && python3 main.py
    # Check SPI devices
    ls /dev/spidev*
    # Enable SPI1 for NRF24L01
    echo 'dtoverlay=spi1-3cs' | sudo tee -a 
    /boot/config.txt
    # Check I2C devices (should show 3c for 
    # OLED)
    i2cdetect -y 1
    # Check display
    tvservice -s ---
